349":"1349","1326":"1326","1348":"1348","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","ABT 1351":"about 1351","1368":"1368","1302":"1302","1278":"1278","1365":"1365","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1328":"1328","1405":"1405","<, Standish, Lancashire, England>":"Standish, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Standish, Lancashire, England":"Standish, Lancashire, England","Hope Manor, Standish, Lancashire, England":"Standish, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lea","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Lee  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 李 and 利, see   Li   1 and 3."],"variants":[{"name":"Lee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sang, Jae, Jong, Jung, Sung, Yong, Kyung, Seung, Dong, Kwang, Myung.","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a meadow or a patch of arable land, Middle English <i>lee</i>, <i>lea</i>, from Old English <i>lēa</i>, dative case (used after a preposition) of <i>lēah</i>, which originally meant ‘wood or glade’.","English: habitational name from any of the many places in England named with Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade’, including Lee in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Kent, and Shropshire, and Lea in Cheshire, Derbyshire, Herefordshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, and Wiltshire."]}]},{"name":"Isolde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The name of the tragic mistress of Tristan in the Arthurian romances. There are several versions of the story. The main features are that the beautiful Isolde, an Irish princess, is betrothed to the aged King Mark of Cornwall. However, through accidentally drinking a magic potion, she and the young Cornish knight Tristan fall in love, with tragic consequences. The story has exercised a powerful hold on the European imagination.